04555nam a2200757Ia 9781503638075DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2023020625  a97815036380757 a10.1515/97815036380752doi  a(DE-B1597)690666  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aBR1644.5.G4 4aBR1644.5.G4bH66 2024 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a362.4/1223/eng/202311151 aHomewood, Nathanael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSeductive Spirits :bDeliverance, Demons, and Sexual Worldmaking in Ghanaian Pentecostalism /cNathanael Homewood. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSpiritual Phenomena00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne Historical and Contemporary Scenes -- tTwo Indecent Scenes -- tThree Singular Scenes -- tFour Scenes of Struggle -- tFive Spousal Scenes -- tSix Serpentine Scenes -- tConclusion: Decolonial Demons -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPentecostalism, Africa's fastest-growing form of Christianity, has long been preoccupied with the business of banishing demons from human bodies. Among Ghanaian Pentecostals, deliverance is primary among the embodied, experiential gifts—a loud, messy, and noisy experience that ends only when the possessed body falls to the ground silent and docile, the evil spirits rendered powerless in the face of the holy spirit-wielding-prophets. And nowhere is Ghanaian Pentecostal obsession with demons more pronounced than with sexual demons. In this book, Nathanael Homewood examines the frequent and varied experiences of spirit possession and sex with demons that constitute a vital part of Pentecostal deliverance ministries, offering insight into these practices assembled from long-term ethnographic engagement with four churches in Accra, the capital of Ghana. Relying on the uniqueness of the Pentecostal sensorium, this book unravels how spirits and sexuality intimately combine to expand the definition of the body beyond its fleshy boundaries. Demons are a knowledge regime, one that shapes how Pentecostals think about, engage with, and construct the cosmos. Deliverance Pentecostals reiterate and tarry with the demonic, especially sexually, as a realm of invention whereby alternative ways of being, sensing, and having sex are dreamed, practiced, and performed. Ultimately, Homewood argues for a distinction between colonial demonization and decolonial demons, charting another path to understanding being, the body, and sexualities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDemoniac possessionzGhana2DLC. 0aDemoniac possessionzGhana. 0aDemonologyxPentecostal churches2DLC. 0aDemonologyxPentecostal churches. 0aExperience (Religion) 0aExperience (Religion)2DLC. 0aExperience (Religion). 0aPentecostalismzGhana2DLC. 0aPentecostalismzGhana. 0aSexxReligious aspectsxPentecostal churches2DLC. 0aSexxReligious aspectsxPentecostal churches. 0aSpirit possessionzGhana2DLC. 0aSpirit possessionzGhana. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aDecolonial.  aDeliverance.  aDemons.  aExorcism.  aGhana.  aPentecostalism.  aSenses.  aSex.  aSpirits.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363807540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503638075423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503638075/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles